                                    <p>
            <lb/>Our S<hi rend="superscript:true;">r</hi>. Martha Clayton was born March
            <lb/>10<hi rend="superscript:true;">th</hi> 1716 at Holbeck near Leeds, Her Parents
            <lb/>who were Dissenters brought her up in a
            <lb/>religious way, &amp; taught her when she was a
            <lb/>Child <unclear>Her</unclear> Catechism &amp; several, &amp; she made such
            <lb/>a proficiency, that a Bible was given her as
            <lb/>a Premium &amp; to encourage her to learn still more.
            <lb/>She was put apprentice to a Man in Wortley
            <lb/>&amp; her behaviour was such that she gained the
            <lb/>love &amp; esteem of her Master &amp; all who lived
            <lb/>in the House w<hi rend="superscript:true;">th</hi> her, here she become uneasy
            <lb/>&amp; concerned ab<hi rend="superscript:true;">r</hi> her Salvation, &amp; when Mr
            <lb/>Ingham began to preach in these parts, she
            <lb/>went to hear him, but as her concern was not
            <lb/>deep it wore of by degrees. -- after this she
            <lb/>married the present W. Joseph Clayton
            <lb/>w<hi rend="superscript:true;">th</hi> whom she has had 7 Children 3 Boys
            <lb/> &amp; 4 girls. <hi rend="superscript:true;">one of whom </hi>went before the Mother into Healths
            <lb/>happy bounds. 1 Son <hi rend="strikethrough:true;">?</hi> a g<hi rend="superscript:true;">r</hi> Boy <hi rend="strikethrough:true;">in the Ch</hi>oir
            <lb/><hi rend="strikethrough:true;">House</hi> &amp; Daughter ^<hi rend="superscript:true;">a</hi> g<hi rend="superscript:true;">r</hi> Girls <hi rend="strikethrough:true;">is</hi> are in the Choir
            <lb/>Houses in Lambs Hill, &amp; 3 Girles &amp; Boy are
            <lb/>at home w<hi rend="superscript:true;">th</hi> their Father.
            <lb/>Sometime after their Marriage her
            <lb/>husband was awaken'd, but she then opposed
            <lb/>his Course &amp; was against his going to hear
            <lb/>Mr Ingham, but when the B<hi rend="superscript:true;">rn</hi> came, her
            <lb/>emotions of Grace were revived, &amp; she went
            <lb/>to hear them, &amp; was soon rec'd in the Society
            <lb/>at Holbeck, since which time she has had an
